f0d31032-2a1f-4ebd-8211-4fa42e11b402.114a7081-1e7b-491c-8936-b077cb9186df.description=
Authenticates against a keystone identity service and returns an authentication token and a list of endpoints available to the specified user. This flow should handle authentication against public/private cloud systems installed using the default procedure outlined in the OpenStack administrators guide, as well as the HP cloud services public cloud. 
There are two endpoints returned by this flow\:  and , which are HP plugin extensions to OpenStack, and these two outputs will be empty if this flow is run against a generic Keystone implementation. 

Inputs\:
    identityServiceEndpoint - The endpoint to which authentication requests are sent. 
Example\: https\://region-a.geo-1.identity.hpcloudsvc.com\:35357/v2.0
    identityServiceUsername - The keystone authentication user name.
Examples\: admin, user@somedomain.com
    identityServicePassword - The keystone authentication password.
Example\: somepassword
    tenantId - The ID of the keystone tenant used in the authentication process.
Examples\: 123456798, 86aae2e3c911436c986999b8d930c073
    computeRegion - The region from which to select the compute endpoint. This is also used for image block storage endpoints. If this input is empty, the first endpoint in the returned array of endpoints is selected. 
Example\: az-2.region-a.geo-1
    objectStorageRegion - The region of the object storage endpoint to select. This region is also used for the CDN endpoint. If the region is not specified, the first endpoint in the returned array of endpoints is selected.
Example\: region-a.geo-1
    username - The user name used for URL authentication. For NTLM authentication, the required format is 'domain\user'.
    password - The password used for URL authentication.
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication)
Default value\: anonymous (no authentication used when executing the request)
    kerberosConfFile - The path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty, the  (Key Distribution Center) and  get their values from the full domain name obtained from the web server URL.
    timeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in  milliseconds. This input needs a value greater than or equal to zero. A  value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
    useCookies - Specifies whether to enable cookie tracking or not. Cookies are stored between consecutive calls. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    proxy - The proxy server used to access the web site.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
    proxyUsername - The proxy server user name.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the  input value.
    encodeURL - Specifies whether to encode the URL or not. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    characterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP 'Get' request and response. 
Default value\: UTF-8
    trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL or not. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    keystore - The location of the KeyStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS client authentication is used. 
Example\: %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file.
    trustKeystore - The location of the TrustStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS server authentication is used. 
Example\: %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts
    trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file.
    headerNamesList - A list of header names to be used for the request.
Example\: Accept,Content-Type
    headerValuesList - A list of header values to be used for the request. 
Example\: text/plain,application/x-www-form-urlencoded
    queryNamesList - A list of query parameter names to be used for the request. 
Example\: parameterName1,parameterName2 
    queryValuesList - A list of query parameter values to be used for the request. 
Example\: parameterValue1,parameterValue2
    delimiter - The delimiter used to separate list elements.
Default value\: (carriage return)

Results\:
    authToken - This is the primary output. The token needed for subsequent API calls.
    FailureMessage - The final error message returned to the user.
    objectStorageEndpoint - The endpoint to use for object storage (swift) API calls.
    cdnEndpoint - The endpoint to use for CDN API calls.
    blockStorageEndpoint- The endpoint to use for block storage API calls.
    computeEndpoint - The endpoint to use for compute (nova) API calls.
    imageEndpoint - The endpoint to use for image (glance) API calls.  
    accessJSONObject - The complete JSON object returned by the authentication request.
    exception - The stack trace of the thrown error (if an error occurred).

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
    unknown - The authentication request resulted in an INFORMATIONAL or REDIRECTION code. This usually means that the request failed.

Note\:
See the 'Library/Operations/HTTP Client/' operations for additional information.
f0d31032-2a1f-4ebd-8211-4fa42e11b402.478633bf-eac0-4db2-87e0-7114319c7221.description=
Accepts an object in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON) and
returns a value for the specified key.

The JSON format encodes objects as a set of unordered key/value pairs, which is
similar to a structure or map in other programming languages.  For example,
   { "city" \: "Palo Alto", 
     "state" \: "CA" }
is an object with two elements one with the name "city" having the value "Palo
Alto", and the other being the name "state" with the value "CA". This operation would 
return "Palo Alto" if user enters "city" as a key.

If the input object contains JSON array, array index can be used in the key input. For example, 
{ "location"\: [
      {"city"\: "Roseville", "country"\: "United States"},
      {"city"\: "Cluj", "country"\: "Romania"},
      {"city"\: "Yehud", "country"\: "Israel"}]    
}
The operation would return "Roseville" if user enters "location[0].city" as a key.

JavaScript objects are useful for representing structured data, and are
especially when used within an array.  For example, an operation that retrieves
a set of incidents from an external system may return the entire list in one
array of incident objects.  The description of the enclosing folder,
/Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and
the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org.

Inputs

   object
      The JavaScript object.  
      The operation will return a failure if it is not a JavaScript object.

   key
      The key in the object to get the value of.

Responses

   success
      The value was successfully returned for the specified key. 

   failure
      There was some error in processing the object, most likely because the
      object is not in valid JavaScript Object Notation or the specified key does not exist in the object.  
      You may wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with
      JavaScript Object Notation.

Outputs

   The primary output will be the value for the specified key in the object.

Note

    If the value in JSON object is in scientific notation, the returned output will be converted to an equivalent decimal number. Ex, 2.9e+1 will be converted to 29.

f0d31032-2a1f-4ebd-8211-4fa42e11b402.62db917b-0c09-4bad-b0df-ae40b53c1aa0.description=
This sample is a copy of the 'OpenStack Dashboard' flow from the 'Compute' folder, having the final 'Notify' step removed and the report information returned as flow result. It is used in the 'OpenStack Dashboard MultiTenant' sample. The returned information is\: number of servers - active or non-active, floating IPs, flavors, images, key pairs and security groups.

Inputs\:
    computeEndpoint - The endpoint to which requests are sent. 
Example\: https\://az-1.region-a.geo-1.compute.hpcloudsvc.com/v1.1/28400914814935
    authToken - The authentication token used for the request.
Example\: HPAuth_4f3b5044e4b05c3dbefdee82
    proxy - The hostname or IP address of the computer that acts as proxy server.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
    proxyUsername - The proxy server user name.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the  input value.

Results\:
    dashboardReport - This is the primary output. The full report with usage information for each tenant. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

f0d31032-2a1f-4ebd-8211-4fa42e11b402.c58e8b1b-8bb7-429c-8738-c87ebbfcd646.description=
Iterates through a JavaScript array, i.e. a string value that contains an array
in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON).  Each time that this operation
is called it places the value of the current array element into the Result
output and advances the iterator to the array element.

The JSON format is basically a way to encode arrays and other values using
JavaScript notation.  For arrays, this means that the values need to be
surrounded by square brackets, and each element in the array can be a string
(which needs surrounding quotes), a number, true, false, null, or a nested array
or object.  Commas are always used as delimiters between array elements, and
they can appear within string elements without confusion.  For example, the
following is a simple JSON array\:
   [ "cat", "dog", "horse" ]
Note that the equivalent OO list would be 
   cat,dog,horse
The benefits of JavaScript arrays are that delimiters are fixed and cannot be
confused with data, and that complex nesting of arrays and objects are
supported.  The description of the enclosing folder, /Library/Utility
Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and the JSON format
is described completely at http\://www.json.org.

Modifying the contents of the array during iteration is not generally supported,
but will be safe as long as the affected item(s) are beyond the current position
of the iterator.  The iterator keeps track of where it is in the array by
position.  If items are added or removed to the list in a position preceding the
iterator, it may cause the iterator to return results that are not obvious.  For
example, if the array contains [ "a", "b", "c" ] and the iterator is positioned
on the second element, "b" and the first element is removed, then the iterator
will now be at the last element in the list, "c".

There is currently a limitation that a flow can only have one of these array
iterator steps active at a time without causing possible conflicts.  In other
words, if you need to iterate through a nested array, you will should use a
sub-flow to process the inner array.  You may have two or more of these array
iterators in the same flow as long as each iterator reaches the end of its array
before the next one begins.

Inputs

   array
      The JavaScript array that will be iterated through.  The operation will
      return a failure if the array is not a JavaScript array; a normal OO list
      is NOT a JavaScript array.

Responses

   has more
      The iterator has not yet reached the end of the array. The Result output
      will be populated with the value of the current element in the array, and
      the iterator will advance to the next element in the array.

   no more
      The iterator has reached the end of the array, and there is no more data
      to return.  The iterator will become undefined after this call, which
      basically will reset it so that if called again, this operation will begin
      another iteration at the beginning of the array.

   failure
      There was some error in iterating through the list, and the Result output
      will contain information about the error.  This will occur if the input
      array is not a valid JavaScript array.  For example, if presented with a
      common list value such as a,b,c it will fail because it lacks the
      enclosing brackets and the quotes around each string element.  You may
      wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose
      problems with JavaScript Object Notation.

Outputs

   Result
      The current array element.  When incorporating this operation into a flow,
      you should assign a meaningful result value from this field.  Note that
      since JavaScript arrays may contain nested arrays or other objects, the
      value returned in Result may also require further processing.
f0d31032-2a1f-4ebd-8211-4fa42e11b402.description=
Retrieves an unscoped token from the keystone service, uses this token to get a list of tenants available for login and then generates a scoped token for each tenant. The scoped tokens are used to generate usage reports for each tenant, obtaining a single large report with information about each login available tenant.

Inputs\:
    identityServiceEndpoint - The endpoint to which authentication requests are sent. 
Example\: https\://region-a.geo-1.identity.hpcloudsvc.com\:35357/v2.0
    identityServiceUsername - The keystone authentication user name.
Examples\: admin, user@somedomain.com
    identityServicePassword - The keystone authentication password.
Example\: somepassword
    username - The user name used for URL authentication. For NTLM authentication, the required format is 'domain\user'.
    password - The password used for URL authentication.
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication)
Default value\: anonymous (no authentication used when executing the request)
    proxy - The proxy server used to access the web site.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
    timeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in  milliseconds. This input needs a value greater than or equal to zero. A  value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
    useCookies - Specifies whether to enable cookie tracking or not. Cookies are stored between consecutive calls. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    followRedirects - Specifies whether the 'Get' command automatically follows redirects or not. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    proxyUsername - The proxy server user name.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the  input value.
    encodeURL - Specifies whether to encode the URL or not. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    userAgent - The value to use if the 'USER_AGENT' HTTP header has to be overwritten.
    characterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP 'Get' request and response. 
Default value\: UTF-8
    trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    keystore - The location of the KeyStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS client authentication is used. The default value will be provided if trustAllRoots is false.
Default\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file. If trustAllRoots is false and keystore is empty, keystorePassword default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    trustKeystore - The location of the TrustStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS server authentication is used. The default value will be provided if trustAllRoots is false.
Default\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
    trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file.  If trustAllRoots is false and trustKeystore is empty, trustPassword default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    kerberosConfFile - The path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty, the  (Key Distribution Center) and  get their values from the full domain name obtained from the web server URL.
    socketTimeout - The time to wait for data to be retrieved, in milliseconds. This input needs a value greater than or equal to zero. A  value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
    headerNamesList - A list of header names to be used for the request.
Example\: Accept,Content-Type
    headerValuesList - A list of header values to be used for the request. 
Example\: text/plain,application/x-www-form-urlencoded
    queryNamesList - A list of query parameter names to be used for the request. The list of servers can be filtered by , ,  and , using the respective query parameters. Image and flavor references can be IDs or full URLs. When retrieving a list of servers using the  parameter, the list will contain all servers that have been deleted since the  date. Servers with an 'ACTIVE'  are available for use. Other possible values for the  attribute include\: 'BUILD', 'REBUILD', 'SUSPENDED', 'RESIZE', 'VERIFY_RESIZE', 'REVERT_RESIZE', 'PASSWORD', 'REBOOT', 'HARD_REBOOT', 'DELETED', 'UNKNOWN' and 'ERROR'.
Example\: parameterName1,parameterName2    
Valid values\: image,flavor,name,status,changes-since,marker,limit
    queryValuesList - A list of query parameter values to be used for the request. 
Example\: parameterValue1,parameterValue2
    delimiter - The delimiter used to separate list elements.
Default value\: (carriage return)

Results\:
    dashboardReport - This is the primary output. A full report with usage information for each tenant. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
See the 'Library/Operations/HTTP Client/' operations for additional information.
